&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What MatX Is Building&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;MatX is seeking engineers with &lt;strong&gt;strong Haskell skills&lt;/strong&gt; to join our team as we create best-in-class silicon for high-performance and sustainable GenAI. The successful candidate for this role will be responsible for delivering performant silicon RTL at the full-chip or subsystem level.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will write hardware in &lt;strong&gt;Bluespec&lt;/strong&gt;, a hardware description language rooted in Haskell&#39;s type system and semantics. If you&#39;ve ever wished you could design hardware with the composability and correctness guarantees of a modern functional language, this is the role for you. &lt;strong&gt;You do not need prior hardware experience to apply — if you know Haskell, we will teach you the hardware side.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What You&#39;ll Do Here&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build production hardware for compute, memory management, and high-speed connectivity&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Develop reusable, parameterized Bluespec libraries that scale across the chip&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Shape hardware architecture by leveraging the power of Bluespec to explore implementation tradeoffs and converge on the best designs&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create innovative tooling for our hardware/software ecosystem to help us build correct, high-performance hardware faster&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Who You Are&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Proficient in &lt;strong&gt;Haskell&lt;/strong&gt; — you&#39;re comfortable with monads, typeclasses, higher-order functions, and do-notation. You understand why return injects a value into a monadic context and what &amp;lt;- does in a do-block&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strongly willing to quickly ramp on &lt;strong&gt;Bluespec Haskell (BH)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strong engineering fundamentals — you write clean, well-tested, well-documented code and are comfortable with build systems, version control, and CI workflows&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bonus Points If You Have&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Existing experience with Bluespec.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Prior hardware design experience — ASIC or FPGA. If you already understand clock domains, pipelining, state machines, synthesis, and timing closure, that&#39;s a significant advantage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Production Rust experience. If you know Haskell, Rust is easy, but if you&#39;ve already used it on something real, that&#39;s a head start&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Getting started with Bluespec:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you&#39;re new to Bluespec, start here:&lt;a href=&quot;https://yehowshuaimmanuel.com/posts/getting-started-with-bluespec/&quot;&gt; Getting Started With Bluespec&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For a hands-on introduction to the language, see Rishiyur Nikhil&#39;s&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/rsnikhil/ICFP2020_Bluespec_Tutorial/blob/master/ICFP2020_Bluespec_Tutorial.adoc&quot;&gt; ICFP 2020 Bluespec Tutorial&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
